# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: catboost
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] In machine learning (ML), **boosting** is an ensemble learning method that combines a set of less accurate models (called "weak learners") to create a single, highly accurate model (a "strong learner").
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Unlike other ensemble methods that build models in parallel (such as bagging), boosting algorithms build models sequentially.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Each new model in the sequence is trained to correct the errors made by its predecessors.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] This iterative process allows the overall model to improve its accuracy, particularly by reducing bias.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Boosting is a popular and effective technique used in supervised learning for both classification and regression tasks.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Robert Schapire's affirmative answer to this question in a 1990 paper led to the development of practical boosting algorithms.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] The first such algorithm was developed by Schapire, with Freund and Schapire later developing AdaBoost, which remains a foundational example of boosting.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] While boosting is not algorithmically constrained, most boosting algorithms consist of iteratively learning weak classifiers with respect to a distribution and adding them to a final strong classifier.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] When they are added, they are weighted in a way that is related to the weak learners' accuracy.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] After a weak learner is added, the data weights are readjusted, known as "re-weighting".
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Misclassified input data gain a higher weight and examples that are classified correctly lose weight.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Thus, future weak learners focus more on the examples that previous weak learners misclassified.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] The original ones, proposed by Robert Schapire (a recursive majority gate formulation), and Yoav Freund (boost by majority), were not adaptive and could not take full advantage of the weak learners.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Schapire and Freund then developed AdaBoost, an adaptive boosting algorithm that won the prestigious Gödel Prize.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Only algorithms that are provable boosting algorithms in the probably approximately correct learning formulation can accurately be called *boosting algorithms*.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Other algorithms that are similar in spirit to boosting algorithms are sometimes called "leveraging algorithms", although they are also sometimes incorrectly called boosting algorithms.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] The main variation between many boosting algorithms is their method of weighting training data points and hypotheses.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] AdaBoost is very popular and the most significant historically as it was the first algorithm that could adapt to the weak learners.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] It is often the basis of introductory coverage of boosting in university machine learning courses.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] There are many more recent algorithms such as LPBoost, TotalBoost, BrownBoost, xgboost, MadaBoost, LogitBoost, CatBoost and others.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Many boosting algorithms fit into the AnyBoost framework, which shows that boosting performs gradient descent in a function space using a convex cost function.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Given images containing various known objects in the world, a classifier can be learned from them to automatically classify the objects in future images.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Simple classifiers built based on some image feature of the object tend to be weak in categorization performance.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Using boosting methods for object categorization is a way to unify the weak classifiers in a special way to boost the overall ability of categorization.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Object categorization is a typical task of computer vision that involves determining whether or not an image contains some specific category of object.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] The idea is closely related with recognition, identification, and detection.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Appearance based object categorization typically contains feature extraction, learning a classifier, and applying the classifier to new examples.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] There are many ways to represent a category of objects, e.g. from shape analysis, bag of words models, or local descriptors such as SIFT, etc.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Examples of supervised classifiers are Naive Bayes classifiers, support vector machines, mixtures of Gaussians, and neural networks.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] However, research has shown that object categories and their locations in images can be discovered in an unsupervised manner as well.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] The recognition of object categories in images is a challenging problem in computer vision, especially when the number of categories is large.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] This is due to high intra class variability and the need for generalization across variations of objects within the same category.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Objects within one category may look quite different.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Even the same object may appear unalike under different viewpoint, scale, and illumination.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Background clutter and partial occlusion add difficulties to recognition as well.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Humans are able to recognize thousands of object types, whereas most of the existing object recognition systems are trained to recognize only a few, e.g. human faces, cars, simple objects, etc.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Research has been very active on dealing with more categories and enabling incremental additions of new categories, and although the general problem remains unsolved, several multi-category objects detectors (for up to hundreds or thousands of categories) have been developed.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] One means is by feature sharing and boosting.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] AdaBoost can be used for face detection as an example of binary categorization.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] The two categories are faces versus background.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] After boosting, a classifier constructed from 200 features could yield a 95% detection rate under a $10^{-5}$ false positive rate.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Another application of boosting for binary categorization is a system that detects pedestrians using patterns of motion and appearance.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] This work is the first to combine both motion information and appearance information as features to detect a walking person.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] It takes a similar approach to the Viola-Jones object detection framework.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Compared with binary categorization, multi-class categorization looks for common features that can be shared across the categories at the same time.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] They turn to be more generic edge like features.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] During learning, the detectors for each category can be trained jointly.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Compared with training separately, it generalizes better, needs less training data, and requires fewer features to achieve the same performance.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] The main flow of the algorithm is similar to the binary case.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] What is different is that a measure of the joint training error shall be defined in advance.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] During each iteration the algorithm chooses a classifier of a single feature (features that can be shared by more categories shall be encouraged).
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] This can be done via converting multi-class classification into a binary one (a set of categories versus the rest), or by introducing a penalty error from the categories that do not have the feature of the classifier.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] In the paper "Sharing visual features for multiclass and multiview object detection", A.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Torralba et al. used GentleBoost for boosting and showed that when training data is limited, learning via sharing features does a much better job than no sharing, given same boosting rounds.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Also, for a given performance level, the total number of features required (and therefore the run time cost of the classifier) for the feature sharing detectors, is observed to scale approximately logarithmically with the number of class, i.e., slower than linear growth in the non-sharing case.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Similar results are shown in the paper "Incremental learning of object detectors using a visual shape alphabet", yet the authors used AdaBoost for boosting.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Boosting algorithms can be based on convex or non-convex optimization algorithms.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] Convex algorithms, such as AdaBoost and LogitBoost, can be "defeated" by random noise such that they can't learn basic and learnable combinations of weak hypotheses.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] This limitation was pointed out by Long & Servedio in 2008.
[src:catboost/boosting-machine-learning] However, by 2009, multiple authors demonstrated that boosting algorithms based on non-convex optimization, such as BrownBoost, can learn from noisy datasets and can specifically learn the underlying classifier of the Long–Servedio dataset.
[src:catboost/catboost] Kaggle listed CatBoost as one of the most frequently used machine learning (ML) frameworks in the world.
[src:catboost/catboost] It was listed as the top-8 most frequently used ML framework in the 2020 survey and as the top-7 most frequently used ML framework in the 2021 survey.
[src:catboost/catboost] In 2009 Andrey Gulin developed MatrixNet, a proprietary gradient boosting library that was used in Yandex to rank search results.
[src:catboost/catboost] Since 2009 MatrixNet has been used in different projects at Yandex, including recommendation systems and weather prediction.
[src:catboost/catboost] In 2014–2015 Andrey Gulin worked with a team of researchers to start a new project called Tensornet which was aimed at solving the problem of "how to work with categorical data".
[src:catboost/catboost] Their work resulted in several proprietary Gradient Boosting libraries with different approaches to handling categorical data.
[src:catboost/catboost] In 2016 the Machine Learning Infrastructure team led by Anna Dorogush started working on Gradient Boosting in Yandex, including Matrixnet and Tensornet.
[src:catboost/catboost] They implemented and open-sourced the next version of Gradient Boosting library called CatBoost, which has support for categorical and text data, GPU training, model analysis, and visualization tools.
[src:catboost/catboost] CatBoost was open-sourced in July 2017 and is under active development in Yandex and the open-source community.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] In computer science and some branches of mathematics, categorical variables are referred to as enumerations or enumerated types.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Commonly (though not in this article), each of the possible values of a categorical variable is referred to as a **level**.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The probability distribution associated with a random categorical variable is called a categorical distribution.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] A categorical variable that can take on exactly two values is termed a *binary variable* or a **dichotomous variable**; an important special case is the Bernoulli variable.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Categorical variables with more than two possible values are called **polytomous variables**; categorical variables are often assumed to be polytomous unless otherwise specified.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Discretization is treating continuous data as if it were categorical.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Dichotomization is treating continuous data or polytomous variables as if they were binary variables.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Regression analysis often treats category membership with one or more quantitative dummy variables.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] For ease in statistical processing, categorical variables may be assigned numeric indices, e.g.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] 1 through *K* for a *K*-way categorical variable (i.e. a variable that can express exactly *K* possible values).
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] In general, however, the numbers are arbitrary, and have no significance beyond simply providing a convenient label for a particular value.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] In other words, the values in a categorical variable exist on a nominal scale: they each represent a logically separate concept, cannot necessarily be meaningfully ordered, and cannot be otherwise manipulated as numbers could be.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Instead, valid operations are equivalence, set membership, and other set-related operations.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] As a result, the central tendency of a set of categorical variables is given by its mode; neither the mean nor the median can be defined.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] As an example, given a set of people, we can consider the set of categorical variables corresponding to their last names.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] We can consider operations such as equivalence (whether two people have the same last name), set membership (whether a person has a name in a given list), counting (how many people have a given last name), or finding the mode (which name occurs most often).
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] However, we cannot meaningfully compute the "sum" of Smith + Johnson, or ask whether Smith is "less than" or "greater than" Johnson.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] As a result, we cannot meaningfully ask what the "average name" (the mean) or the "middle-most name" (the median) is in a set of names.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] This ignores the concept of alphabetical order, which is a property that is not inherent in the names themselves, but in the way we construct the labels.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] However, if we do consider the names as written, e.g., in the Latin alphabet, and define an ordering corresponding to standard alphabetical order, then we have effectively converted them into ordinal variables defined on an ordinal scale.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Categorical random variables are normally described statistically by a categorical distribution, which allows an arbitrary *K*-way categorical variable to be expressed with separate probabilities specified for each of the *K* possible outcomes.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Such multiple-category categorical variables are often analyzed using a multinomial distribution, which counts the frequency of each possible combination of numbers of occurrences of the various categories.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Regression analysis on categorical outcomes is accomplished through multinomial logistic regression, multinomial probit or a related type of discrete choice model.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Categorical variables that have only two possible outcomes (e.g., "yes" vs.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] "failure") are known as *binary variables* (or *Bernoulli variables*).
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Because of their importance, these variables are often considered a separate category, with a separate distribution (the Bernoulli distribution) and separate regression models (logistic regression, probit regression, etc.).
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] As a result, the term "categorical variable" is often reserved for cases with 3 or more outcomes, sometimes termed a *multi-way* variable in opposition to a binary variable.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] It is also possible to consider categorical variables where the number of categories is not fixed in advance.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] As an example, for a categorical variable describing a particular word, we might not know in advance the size of the vocabulary, and we would like to allow for the possibility of encountering words that we have not already seen.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Standard statistical models, such as those involving the categorical distribution and multinomial logistic regression, assume that the number of categories is known in advance, and changing the number of categories on the fly is tricky.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] In such cases, more advanced techniques must be used.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] An example is the Dirichlet process, which falls in the realm of nonparametric statistics.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] In such a case, it is logically assumed that an infinite number of categories exist, but at any one time most of them (in fact, all but a finite number) have never been seen.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] All formulas are phrased in terms of the number of categories actually seen so far rather than the (infinite) total number of potential categories in existence, and methods are created for incremental updating of statistical distributions, including adding "new" categories.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Categorical variables represent a qualitative method of scoring data (i.e. represents categories or group membership).
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] These can be included as independent variables in a regression analysis or as dependent variables in logistic regression or probit regression, but must be converted to quantitative data in order to be able to analyze the data.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] One does so through the use of coding systems.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Analyses are conducted such that only *g* -1 (*g* being the number of groups) are coded.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] This minimizes redundancy while still representing the complete data set as no additional information would be gained from coding the total *g* groups: for example, when coding gender (where *g* = 2: male and female), if we only code females everyone left over would necessarily be males.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] In general, the group that one does not code for is the group of least interest.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] There are three main coding systems typically used in the analysis of categorical variables in regression: dummy coding, effects coding, and contrast coding.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The regression equation takes the form of ***Y = bX + a***, where *b* is the slope and gives the weight empirically assigned to an explanator, *X* is the explanatory variable, and *a* is the *Y*-intercept, and these values take on different meanings based on the coding system used.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The choice of coding system does not affect the *F* or *R*2 statistics.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] However, one chooses a coding system based on the comparison of interest since the interpretation of *b* values will vary.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Dummy coding is used when there is a control or comparison group in mind.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] One is therefore analyzing the data of one group in relation to the comparison group: *a* represents the mean of the control group and *b* is the difference between the mean of the experimental group and the mean of the control group.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] In dummy coding, the reference group is assigned a value of 0 for each code variable, the group of interest for comparison to the reference group is assigned a value of 1 for its specified code variable, while all other groups are assigned 0 for that particular code variable.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The *b* values should be interpreted such that the experimental group is being compared against the control group.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Therefore, yielding a negative b value would entail the experimental group have scored less than the control group on the dependent variable.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] To illustrate this, suppose that we are measuring optimism among several nationalities and we have decided that French people would serve as a useful control.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] If we are comparing them against Italians, and we observe a negative *b* value, this would suggest Italians obtain lower optimism scores on average.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] In the effects coding system, data are analyzed through comparing one group to all other groups.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Unlike dummy coding, there is no control group.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Rather, the comparison is being made at the mean of all groups combined (*a* is now the grand mean).
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Therefore, one is not looking for data in relation to another group but rather, one is seeking data in relation to the grand mean.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Effects coding can either be weighted or unweighted.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Weighted effects coding is simply calculating a weighted grand mean, thus taking into account the sample size in each variable.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] This is most appropriate in situations where the sample is representative of the population in question.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Unweighted effects coding is most appropriate in situations where differences in sample size are the result of incidental factors.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The interpretation of *b* is different for each: in unweighted effects coding *b* is the difference between the mean of the experimental group and the grand mean, whereas in the weighted situation it is the mean of the experimental group minus the weighted grand mean.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] In effects coding, we code the group of interest with a 1, just as we would for dummy coding.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The principal difference is that we code −1 for the group we are least interested in.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Since we continue to use a *g* - 1 coding scheme, it is in fact the −1 coded group that will not produce data, hence the fact that we are least interested in that group.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] A code of 0 is assigned to all other groups.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The *b* values should be interpreted such that the experimental group is being compared against the mean of all groups combined (or weighted grand mean in the case of weighted effects coding).
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Therefore, yielding a negative *b* value would entail the coded group as having scored less than the mean of all groups on the dependent variable.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Using our previous example of optimism scores among nationalities, if the group of interest is Italians, observing a negative *b* value suggest they obtain a lower optimism score.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The following table is an example of effects coding with *Other* as the group of least interest.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The contrast coding system allows a researcher to directly ask specific questions.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Rather than having the coding system dictate the comparison being made (i.e., against a control group as in dummy coding, or against all groups as in effects coding) one can design a unique comparison catering to one's specific research question.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] This tailored hypothesis is generally based on previous theory and/or research.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The hypotheses proposed are generally as follows: first, there is the central hypothesis which postulates a large difference between two sets of groups; the second hypothesis suggests that within each set, the differences among the groups are small.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Through its a priori focused hypotheses, contrast coding may yield an increase in power of the statistical test when compared with the less directed previous coding systems.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Certain differences emerge when we compare our a priori coefficients between ANOVA and regression.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Unlike when used in ANOVA, where it is at the researcher's discretion whether they choose coefficient values that are either orthogonal or non-orthogonal, in regression, it is essential that the coefficient values assigned in contrast coding be orthogonal.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Furthermore, in regression, coefficient values must be either in fractional or decimal form.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The difference between the sum of the positive coefficients and the sum of the negative coefficients should equal 1.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Violating rule 2 produces accurate *R*2 and *F* values, indicating that we would reach the same conclusions about whether or not there is a significant difference; however, we can no longer interpret the *b* values as a mean difference.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] To illustrate the construction of contrast codes consider the following table.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Coefficients were chosen to illustrate our a priori hypotheses: Hypothesis 1: French and Italian persons will score higher on optimism than Germans (French = +0.33, Italian = +0.33, German = −0.66).
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] This is illustrated through assigning the same coefficient to the French and Italian categories and a different one to the Germans.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The signs assigned indicate the direction of the relationship (hence giving Germans a negative sign is indicative of their lower hypothesized optimism scores).
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Hypothesis 2: French and Italians are expected to differ on their optimism scores (French = +0.50, Italian = −0.50, German = 0).
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Here, assigning a zero value to Germans demonstrates their non-inclusion in the analysis of this hypothesis.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Again, the signs assigned are indicative of the proposed relationship.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Nonsense coding occurs when one uses arbitrary values in place of the designated "0"s "1"s and "-1"s seen in the previous coding systems.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Although it produces correct mean values for the variables, the use of nonsense coding is not recommended as it will lead to uninterpretable statistical results.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] An interaction may arise when considering the relationship among three or more variables, and describes a situation in which the simultaneous influence of two variables on a third is not additive.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Interactions may arise with categorical variables in two ways: either categorical by categorical variable interactions, or categorical by continuous variable interactions.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] This type of interaction arises when we have two categorical variables.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] In order to probe this type of interaction, one would code using the system that addresses the researcher's hypothesis most appropriately.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] The product of the codes yields the interaction.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] One may then calculate the *b* value and determine whether the interaction is significant.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Simple slopes analysis is a common post hoc test used in regression which is similar to the simple effects analysis in ANOVA, used to analyze interactions.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] In this test, we are examining the simple slopes of one independent variable at specific values of the other independent variable.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] Such a test is not limited to use with continuous variables, but may also be employed when the independent variable is categorical.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] In our categorical case we would use a simple regression equation for each group to investigate the simple slopes.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] It is common practice to standardize or center variables to make the data more interpretable in simple slopes analysis; however, categorical variables should never be standardized or centered.
[src:catboost/categorical-variable] This test can be used with all coding systems.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Tree models where the target variable can take a discrete set of values are called **classification trees**; in these tree structures, leaves represent class labels and branches represent conjunctions of features that lead to those class labels.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Decision trees where the target variable can take continuous values (typically real numbers) are called **regression trees**.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] More generally, the concept of regression tree can be extended to any kind of object equipped with pairwise dissimilarities such as categorical sequences.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Decision trees are among the most popular machine learning algorithms given their intelligibility and simplicity because they produce algorithms that are easy to interpret and visualize, even for users without a statistical background.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] In decision analysis, a decision tree can be used to visually and explicitly represent decisions and decision making.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] In data mining, a decision tree describes data (but the resulting classification tree can be an input for decision making).
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Decision tree learning is a method commonly used in data mining.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The goal is to create an algorithm that predicts the value of a target variable based on several input variables.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] A decision tree is a simple representation for classifying examples.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] For this section, assume that all of the input features have finite discrete domains, and there is a single target feature called the "classification".
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Each element of the domain of the classification is called a *class*.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] A decision tree or a classification tree is a tree in which each internal (non-leaf) node is labeled with an input feature.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The arcs coming from a node labeled with an input feature are labeled with each of the possible values of the target feature or the arc leads to a subordinate decision node on a different input feature.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] A tree is built by splitting the source set, constituting the root node of the tree, into subsets—which constitute the successor children.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The splitting is based on a set of splitting rules based on classification features.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] This process is repeated on each derived subset in a recursive manner called recursive partitioning.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The recursion is completed when the subset at a node has all the same values of the target variable, or when splitting no longer adds value to the predictions.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] This process of *top-down induction of decision trees* (TDIDT) is an example of a greedy algorithm, and it is by far the most common strategy for learning decision trees from data.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] In data mining, decision trees can be described also as the combination of mathematical and computational techniques to aid the description, categorization and generalization of a given set of data.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The dependent variable, Y , is the target variable that we are trying to understand, classify or generalize.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The vector ${\textbf {x}}$ is composed of the features, $x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}$ etc., that are used for that task.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The term **classification and regression tree (CART)** analysis is an umbrella term used to refer to either of the above procedures, first introduced by Breiman et al.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Trees used for regression and trees used for classification have some similarities – but also some differences, such as the procedure used to determine where to split.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] A special case of a decision tree is a decision list, which is a one-sided decision tree, so that every internal node has exactly 1 leaf node and exactly 1 internal node as a child (except for the bottommost node, whose only child is a single leaf node).
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] While less expressive, decision lists are arguably easier to understand than general decision trees due to their added sparsity, permit non-greedy learning methods and monotonic constraints to be imposed.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] ID3 and CART were invented independently at around the same time (between 1970 and 1980), yet follow a similar approach for learning a decision tree from training tuples.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] It has also been proposed to leverage concepts of fuzzy set theory for the definition of a special version of decision tree, known as Fuzzy Decision Tree (FDT).
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] In this type of fuzzy classification, generally, an input vector ${\textbf {x}}$ is associated with multiple classes, each with a different confidence value.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Boosted ensembles of FDTs have been recently investigated as well, and they have shown performances comparable to those of other very efficient fuzzy classifiers.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Algorithms for constructing decision trees usually work top-down, by choosing a variable at each step that best splits the set of items.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Different algorithms use different metrics for measuring "best".
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] These generally measure the homogeneity of the target variable within the subsets.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] These metrics are applied to each candidate subset, and the resulting values are combined (e.g., averaged) to provide a measure of the quality of the split.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Depending on the underlying metric, the performance of various heuristic algorithms for decision tree learning may vary significantly.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] A simple and effective metric can be used to identify the degree to which true positives outweigh false positives (see Confusion matrix).
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] In this equation, the total false positives (FP) are subtracted from the total true positives (TP).
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The resulting number gives an estimate on how many positive examples the feature could correctly identify within the data, with higher numbers meaning that the feature could correctly classify more positive samples.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Here we can see that the TP value would be 8 and the FP value would be 2 (the underlined numbers in the table).
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] When we plug these numbers in the equation we are able to calculate the estimate: $E_{p}=TP-FP=8-2=6$ .
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] This means that using the estimate on this feature would have it receive a score of 6.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] However, it should be worth noting that this number is only an estimate.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] For example, if two features both had a FP value of 2 while one of the features had a higher TP value, that feature would be ranked higher than the other because the resulting estimate when using the equation would give a higher value.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] This could lead to some inaccuracies when using the metric if some features have more positive samples than others.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] To combat this, one could use a more powerful metric known as Sensitivity that takes into account the proportions of the values from the confusion matrix to give the actual true positive rate (TPR).
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] In this example, Feature A had an estimate of 6 and a TPR of approximately 0.73 while Feature B had an estimate of 4 and a TPR of 0.75.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] This shows that although the positive estimate for some feature may be higher, the more accurate TPR value for that feature may be lower when compared to other features that have a lower positive estimate.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Depending on the situation and knowledge of the data and decision trees, one may opt to use the positive estimate for a quick and easy solution to their problem.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] On the other hand, a more experienced user would most likely prefer to use the TPR value to rank the features because it takes into account the proportions of the data and all the samples that should have been classified as positive.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] For a set of items with J classes and relative frequencies $p_{i}$ , $i\in \{1,2,...,J\}$ , the probability of choosing an item with label i is $p_{i}$ , and the probability of miscategorizing that item is $\sum _{k\neq i}p_{k}=1-p_{i}$ .
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The Gini impurity is also an information theoretic measure and corresponds to Tsallis Entropy with deformation coefficient $q=2$ , which in physics is associated with the lack of information in out-of-equilibrium, non-extensive, dissipative and quantum systems.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] For the limit $q\to 1$ one recovers the usual Boltzmann-Gibbs or Shannon entropy.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] In this sense, the Gini impurity is nothing but a variation of the usual entropy measure for decision trees.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Used by the ID3, C4.5 and C5.0 tree-generation algorithms, information gain is based on the concept of entropy and information content from information theory.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] where $p_{1},p_{2},\ldots$ are fractions that add up to 1 and represent the percentage of each class present in the child node that results from a split in the tree.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] That is, the expected information gain is the mutual information, meaning that on average, the reduction in the entropy of *T* is the mutual information.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Information gain is used to decide which feature to split on at each step in building the tree.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Simplicity is best, so we want to keep our tree small.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] To do so, at each step we should choose the split that results in the most consistent child nodes.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] A commonly used measure of consistency is called information which is measured in bits.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] For each node of the tree, the information value "represents the expected amount of information that would be needed to specify whether a new instance should be classified yes or no, given that the example reached that node".
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Consider an example data set with four attributes: *outlook* (sunny, overcast, rainy), *temperature* (hot, mild, cool), *humidity* (high, normal), and *windy* (true, false), with a binary (yes or no) target variable, *play*, and 14 data points.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] To construct a decision tree on this data, we need to compare the information gain of each of four trees, each split on one of the four features.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The split with the highest information gain will be taken as the first split and the process will continue until all child nodes each have consistent data, or until the information gain is 0.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] To find the information gain of the split using *windy*, we must first calculate the information in the data before the split.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The original data contained nine yes's and five no's.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The split using the feature *windy* results in two child nodes, one for a *windy* value of true and one for a *windy* value of false.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] In this data set, there are six data points with a true *windy* value, three of which have a *play* (where *play* is the target variable) value of yes and three with a *play* value of no.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The eight remaining data points with a *windy* value of false contain two no's and six yes's.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The information of the *windy*=true node is calculated using the entropy equation above.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] For the node where *windy*=false there were eight data points, six yes's and two no's.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] To find the information of the split, we take the weighted average of these two numbers based on how many observations fell into which node.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Now we can calculate the information gain achieved by splitting on the *windy* feature.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] To build the tree, the information gain of each possible first split would need to be calculated.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The best first split is the one that provides the most information gain.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] This process is repeated for each impure node until the tree is complete.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] This example is adapted from the example appearing in Witten et al.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Information gain is also known as Shannon index in bio diversity research.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Introduced in CART, variance reduction is often employed in cases where the target variable is continuous (regression tree), meaning that use of many other metrics would first require discretization before being applied.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] where S , $S_{t}$ , and $S_{f}$ are the set of presplit sample indices, set of sample indices for which the split test is true, and set of sample indices for which the split test is false, respectively.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Each of the above summands are indeed variance estimates, though, written in a form without directly referring to the mean.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] By replacing $(y_{i}-y_{j})^{2}$ in the formula above with the dissimilarity $d_{ij}$ between two objects i and j , the variance reduction criterion applies to any kind of object for which pairwise dissimilarities can be computed.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Used by CART in 1984, the measure of "goodness" is a function that seeks to optimize the balance of a candidate split's capacity to create pure children with its capacity to create equally-sized children.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Consider an example data set with three attributes: *savings*(low, medium, high), *assets*(low, medium, high), *income*(numerical value), and a binary target variable *credit risk*(good, bad) and 8 data points.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The full data is presented in the table below.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] To start a decision tree, we will calculate the maximum value of $\varphi (s\mid t)$ using each feature to find which one will split the root node.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] This process will continue until all children are pure or all $\varphi (s\mid t)$ values are below a set threshold.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] To find $\varphi (s\mid t)$ of the feature *savings*, we need to note the quantity of each value.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The original data contained three low's, three medium's, and two high's.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Out of the low's, one had a good *credit risk* while out of the medium's and high's, 4 had a good *credit risk*.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Assume a candidate split s such that records with a low *savings* will be put in the left child and all other records will be put into the right child.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] To build the tree, the "goodness" of all candidate splits for the root node need to be calculated.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The candidate with the maximum value will split the root node, and the process will continue for each impure node until the tree is complete.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Compared to other metrics such as information gain, the measure of "goodness" will attempt to create a more balanced tree, leading to more-consistent decision time.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] However, it sacrifices some priority for creating pure children which can lead to additional splits that are not present with other metrics.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Many data mining software packages provide implementations of one or more decision tree algorithms (e.g. random forest).
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] In a decision tree, all paths from the root node to the leaf node proceed by way of conjunction, or *AND*.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] In a decision graph, it is possible to use disjunctions (ORs) to join two more paths together using minimum message length (MML).
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Decision graphs have been further extended to allow for previously unstated new attributes to be learnt dynamically and used at different places within the graph.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The more general coding scheme results in better predictive accuracy and log-loss probabilistic scoring.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] In general, decision graphs infer models with fewer leaves than decision trees.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Evolutionary algorithms have been used to avoid local optimal decisions and search the decision tree space with little *a priori* bias.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] It is also possible for a tree to be sampled using MCMC.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] The tree can be searched for in a bottom-up fashion.
[src:catboost/decision-tree-learning] Or several trees can be constructed parallelly to reduce the expected number of tests till classification.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] The idea of gradient boosting originated in the observation by Leo Breiman that boosting can be interpreted as an optimization algorithm on a suitable cost function.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Explicit regression gradient boosting algorithms were subsequently developed, by Jerome H.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Friedman, (in 1999 and later in 2001) simultaneously with the more general functional gradient boosting perspective of Llew Mason, Jonathan Baxter, Peter Bartlett and Marcus Frean.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] The latter two papers introduced the view of boosting algorithms as iterative *functional gradient descent* algorithms.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] That is, algorithms that optimize a cost function over function space by iteratively choosing a function (weak hypothesis) that points in the negative gradient direction.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] This functional gradient view of boosting has led to the development of boosting algorithms in many areas of machine learning and statistics beyond regression and classification.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Like other boosting methods, gradient boosting combines weak "learners" into a single strong learner iteratively.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] If the algorithm has M stages, at each stage m ( $1\leq m\leq M$ ), suppose some imperfect model $F_{m}$ (for low m , this model may simply predict ${\hat {y}}_{i}$ to be ${\bar {y}}$ , the mean of y ).
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] In order to improve $F_{m}$ , our algorithm should add some new estimator, $h_{m}(x)$ .
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Therefore, gradient boosting will fit $h_{m}$ to the *residual* $y_{i}-F_{m}(x_{i})$ .
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] As in other boosting variants, each $F_{m+1}$ attempts to correct the errors of its predecessor $F_{m}$ .
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] So, gradient boosting could be generalized to a gradient descent algorithm by plugging in a different loss and its gradient.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Many supervised learning problems involve an output variable y and a vector of input variables x, related to each other with some probabilistic distribution.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] The goal is to find some function ${\hat {F}}(x)$ that best approximates the output variable from the values of input variables.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] The gradient boosting method assumes a real-valued y.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] where $\gamma _{m}$ is the weight at stage m .
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] We are usually given a training set $\{(x_{1},y_{1}),\dots ,(x_{n},y_{n})\}$ of known values of x and corresponding values of y.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] In accordance with the empirical risk minimization principle, the method tries to find an approximation ${\hat {F}}(x)$ that minimizes the average value of the loss function on the training set, i.e., minimizes the empirical risk.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] for $m\geq 1$ , where $h_{m}\in {\mathcal {H}}$ is a base learner function.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Unfortunately, choosing the best function $h_{m}$ at each step for an arbitrary loss function L is a computationally infeasible optimization problem in general.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Therefore, we restrict our approach to a simplified version of the problem.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] The idea is to apply a steepest descent step to this minimization problem (functional gradient descent).
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] The basic idea is to find a local minimum of the loss function by iterating on $F_{m-1}(x)$ .
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] In fact, the local maximum-descent direction of the loss function is the negative gradient.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Note that this approach is a heuristic and therefore doesn't yield an exact solution to the given problem, but rather an approximation.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Fit a base learner (or weak learner, e.g. tree) closed under scaling $h_{m}(x)$ to pseudo-residuals, i.e. train it using the training set $\{(x_{i},r_{im})\}_{i=1}^{n}$ .
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting is typically used with decision trees (especially CARTs) of a fixed size as base learners.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] For this special case, Friedman proposes a modification to gradient boosting method which improves the quality of fit of each base learner.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Generic gradient boosting at the *m*-th step would fit a decision tree $h_{m}(x)$ to pseudo-residuals.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Let $J_{m}$ be the number of its leaves.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] The tree partitions the input space into $J_{m}$ disjoint regions $R_{1m},\ldots ,R_{J_{m}m}$ and predicts a constant value in each region.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] where $b_{jm}$ is the value predicted in the region $R_{jm}$ .
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Friedman proposes to modify this algorithm so that it chooses a separate optimal value $\gamma _{jm}$ for each of the tree's regions, instead of a single $\gamma _{m}$ for the whole tree.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] He calls the modified algorithm "TreeBoost".
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] When the loss $L(\cdot ,\cdot )$ is mean-squared error (MSE) the coefficients $\gamma _{jm}$ coincide with the coefficients of the tree-fitting procedure $b_{jm}$ .
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] The number J of terminal nodes in the trees is a parameter which controls the maximum allowed level of interaction between variables in the model.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] With $J=2$ (decision stumps), no interaction between variables is allowed.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] With $J=3$ the model may include effects of the interaction between up to two variables, and so on.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] J can be adjusted for a data set at hand.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Hastie et al. comment that typically $4\leq J\leq 8$ work well for boosting and results are fairly insensitive to the choice of J in this range, $J=2$ is insufficient for many applications, and $J>10$ is unlikely to be required.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Fitting the training set too closely can lead to degradation of the model's generalization ability, that is, its performance on unseen examples.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Several so-called regularization techniques reduce this overfitting effect by constraining the fitting procedure.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] One natural regularization parameter is the number of gradient boosting iterations *M* (i.e. the number of base models).
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Increasing *M* reduces the error on training set, but increases risk of overfitting.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] An optimal value of *M* is often selected by monitoring prediction error on a separate validation data set.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Another regularization parameter for tree boosting is tree depth.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] The higher this value the more likely the model will overfit the training data.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] where parameter $\nu$ is called the "learning rate".
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Empirically, it has been found that using small learning rates (such as $\nu <0.1$ ) yields dramatic improvements in models' generalization ability over gradient boosting without shrinking ( $\nu =1$ ).
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] However, it comes at the price of increasing computational time both during training and querying: lower learning rate requires more iterations.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Soon after the introduction of gradient boosting, Friedman proposed a minor modification to the algorithm, motivated by Breiman's bootstrap aggregation ("bagging") method.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Specifically, he proposed that at each iteration of the algorithm, a base learner should be fit on a subsample of the training set drawn at random without replacement.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Friedman observed a substantial improvement in gradient boosting's accuracy with this modification.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Subsample size is some constant fraction f of the size of the training set.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] When $f=1$ , the algorithm is deterministic and identical to the one described above.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Smaller values of f introduce randomness into the algorithm and help prevent overfitting, acting as a kind of regularization.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] The algorithm also becomes faster, because regression trees have to be fit to smaller datasets at each iteration.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Friedman obtained that $0.5\leq f\leq 0.8$ leads to good results for small and moderate sized training sets.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Therefore, f is typically set to 0.5, meaning that one half of the training set is used to build each base learner.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Also, like in bagging, subsampling allows one to define an out-of-bag error of the prediction performance improvement by evaluating predictions on those observations which were not used in the building of the next base learner.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Out-of-bag estimates help avoid the need for an independent validation dataset, but often underestimate actual performance improvement and the optimal number of iterations.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Gradient tree boosting implementations often also use regularization by limiting the minimum number of observations in trees' terminal nodes.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] It is used in the tree building process by ignoring any splits that lead to nodes containing fewer than this number of training set instances.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Imposing this limit helps to reduce variance in predictions at leaves.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Another useful regularization technique for gradient boosted model is to penalize its complexity.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] For gradient boosted trees, model complexity can be defined as the proportional number of leaves in the trees.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] The joint optimization of loss and model complexity corresponds to a post-pruning algorithm to remove branches that fail to reduce the loss by a threshold.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Other kinds of regularization such as an $\ell _{2}$ penalty on the leaf values can also be used to avoid overfitting.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting can be used in the field of learning to rank.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] The commercial web search engines Yahoo and Yandex use variants of gradient boosting in their machine-learned ranking engines.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting is also utilized in High Energy Physics in data analysis.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] At the Large Hadron Collider (LHC), variants of gradient boosting Deep Neural Networks (DNN) were successful in reproducing the results of non-machine learning methods of analysis on datasets used to discover the Higgs boson.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting decision tree was also applied in earth and geological studies – for example quality evaluation of sandstone reservoir.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Friedman introduced his regression technique as a "Gradient Boosting Machine" (GBM).
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Mason, Baxter et al. described the generalized abstract class of algorithms as "functional gradient boosting".
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Friedman et al. describe an advancement of gradient boosted models as Multiple Additive Regression Trees (MART); Elith et al. describe that approach as "Boosted Regression Trees" (BRT).
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] A popular open-source implementation for R calls it a "Generalized Boosting Model", however packages expanding this work use BRT.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Yet another name is TreeNet, after an early commercial implementation from Salford System's Dan Steinberg, one of researchers who pioneered the use of tree-based methods.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting can be used for feature importance ranking, which is usually based on aggregating importance function of the base learners.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] For example, if a gradient boosted trees algorithm is developed using entropy-based decision trees, the ensemble algorithm ranks the importance of features based on entropy as well with the caveat that it is averaged out over all base learners.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] While boosting can increase the accuracy of a base learner, such as a decision tree or linear regression, it sacrifices intelligibility and interpretability.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] For example, following the path that a decision tree takes to make its decision is trivial and self-explained, but following the paths of hundreds or thousands of trees is much harder.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] To achieve both performance and interpretability, some model compression techniques allow transforming an XGBoost into a single "born-again" decision tree that approximates the same decision function.
[src:catboost/gradient-boosting] Furthermore, its implementation may be more difficult due to the higher computational demand.
[src:catboost/overfitting] In mathematical modeling, **overfitting** is the production of an analysis that corresponds too closely or exactly to a particular set of data, and may therefore fail to fit to additional data or predict future observations reliably.
[src:catboost/overfitting] An **overfitted model** is a mathematical model that contains more parameters than can be justified by the data.
[src:catboost/overfitting] In the special case of a model that consists of a polynomial function, these parameters represent the degree of a polynomial.
[src:catboost/overfitting] The essence of overfitting is to unknowingly extract some of the residual variation (i.e., noise) as if that variation represents the underlying model structure.
[src:catboost/overfitting] The possibility of over-fitting exists when the criterion used for selecting the model is not the same as the criterion used to judge the suitability of a model.
[src:catboost/overfitting] As an extreme example, if the number of parameters is the same as or greater than the number of observations, then a model can perfectly predict the training data simply by memorizing the data in its entirety.
[src:catboost/overfitting] (For an illustration, see Figure 2.) Such a model will typically fail severely when making predictions.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Overfitting is related to both the complexity of the chosen model and how well it is optimized during training.
[src:catboost/overfitting] A function class that is too large, in a suitable sense, relative to the dataset size is likely to overfit.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Even when the fitted model does not have an excessive number of parameters, it is to be expected that the fitted relationship will appear to perform less well on a new dataset than on the dataset used for fitting (a phenomenon sometimes known as *shrinkage*).
[src:catboost/overfitting] In particular, the value of the coefficient of determination will shrink relative to the original data.
[src:catboost/overfitting] To lessen the chance or amount of overfitting, several techniques are available (e.g., model comparison, cross-validation, regularization, early stopping, pruning, Bayesian priors, or dropout).
[src:catboost/overfitting] The basis of some techniques is to either (1) explicitly penalize overly complex models or (2) test the model's ability to generalize by evaluating its performance on a set of data not used for training, which is assumed to approximate the typical unseen data that a model will encounter.
[src:catboost/overfitting] In statistics, an inference is drawn from a statistical model, which has been selected via some procedure.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Burnham & Anderson, in their much-cited text on model selection, argue that to avoid overfitting, one should adhere to the "Principle of Parsimony".
[src:catboost/overfitting] Overfitting is more likely to be a serious concern when there is little theory available to guide the analysis, in part because then there tend to be a large number of models to select from.
[src:catboost/overfitting] The book *Model Selection and Model Averaging* (2008) puts it this way.
[src:catboost/overfitting] In regression analysis, overfitting occurs frequently.
[src:catboost/overfitting] As an extreme example, if there are *p* variables in a linear regression with *p* data points, the fitted line can go exactly through every point.
[src:catboost/overfitting] For logistic regression or Cox proportional hazards models, there are a variety of rules of thumb (e.g.
[src:catboost/overfitting] 5–9, 10 and 10–15 — the guideline of 10 observations per independent variable is known as the "one in ten rule").
[src:catboost/overfitting] In the process of regression model selection, the mean squared error of the random regression function can be split into random noise, approximation bias, and variance in the estimate of the regression function.
[src:catboost/overfitting] The bias–variance tradeoff is often used to overcome overfit models.
[src:catboost/overfitting] With a large set of explanatory variables that actually have no relation to the dependent variable being predicted, some variables will in general be falsely found to be statistically significant and the researcher may thus retain them in the model, thereby overfitting the model.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Usually, a learning algorithm is trained using some set of "training data": exemplary situations for which the desired output is known.
[src:catboost/overfitting] The goal is that the algorithm will also perform well on predicting the output when fed "validation data" that was not encountered during its training.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Overfitting is the use of models or procedures that violate Occam's razor, for example by including more adjustable parameters than are ultimately optimal, or by using a more complicated approach than is ultimately optimal.
[src:catboost/overfitting] For an example where there are too many adjustable parameters, consider a dataset where training data for y can be adequately predicted by a linear function of two independent variables.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Such a function requires only three parameters (the intercept and two slopes).
[src:catboost/overfitting] Replacing this simple function with a new, more complex quadratic function, or with a new, more complex linear function on more than two independent variables, carries a risk: Occam's razor implies that any given complex function is *a priori* less probable than any given simple function.
[src:catboost/overfitting] When comparing different types of models, complexity cannot be measured solely by counting how many parameters exist in each model; the expressivity of each parameter must be considered as well.
[src:catboost/overfitting] For example, it is nontrivial to directly compare the complexity of a neural net (which can track curvilinear relationships) with m parameters to a regression model with n parameters.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Overfitting is especially likely in cases where learning was performed too long or where training examples are rare, causing the learner to adjust to very specific random features of the training data that have no causal relation to the target function.
[src:catboost/overfitting] In this process of overfitting, the performance on the training examples still increases while the performance on unseen data becomes worse.
[src:catboost/overfitting] As a simple example, consider a database of retail purchases that includes the item bought, the purchaser, and the date and time of purchase.
[src:catboost/overfitting] It's easy to construct a model that will fit the training set perfectly by using the date and time of purchase to predict the other attributes, but this model will not generalize at all to new data because those past times will never occur again.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Generally, a learning algorithm is said to overfit relative to a simpler one if it is more accurate in fitting known data (hindsight) but less accurate in predicting new data (foresight).
[src:catboost/overfitting] One can intuitively understand overfitting from the fact that information from all past experience can be divided into two groups: information that is relevant for the future, and irrelevant information ("noise").
[src:catboost/overfitting] Everything else being equal, the more difficult a criterion is to predict (i.e., the higher its uncertainty), the more noise exists in past information that needs to be ignored.
[src:catboost/overfitting] The problem is determining which part to ignore.
[src:catboost/overfitting] may produce outputs that are virtually identical to instances from their training set.
[src:catboost/overfitting] The most obvious consequence of overfitting is poor performance on the validation dataset.
[src:catboost/overfitting] The optimal function usually needs verification on bigger or completely new datasets.
[src:catboost/overfitting] There are, however, methods like minimum spanning tree or life-time of correlation that applies the dependence between correlation coefficients and time-series (window width).
[src:catboost/overfitting] Whenever the window width is big enough, the correlation coefficients are stable and don't depend on the window width size anymore.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Therefore, a correlation matrix can be created by calculating a coefficient of correlation between investigated variables.
[src:catboost/overfitting] This matrix can be represented topologically as a complex network where direct and indirect influences between variables are visualized.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Dropout regularisation (random removal of training set data) can also improve robustness and therefore reduce over-fitting by probabilistically removing inputs to a layer.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Pruning is another technique that mitigates overfitting and enhances generalization by identifying a sparse, optimal neural network structure, while simultaneously reducing the computational cost of both training and inference.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Underfitting is the inverse of overfitting, meaning that the statistical model or machine learning algorithm is too simplistic to accurately capture the patterns in the data.
[src:catboost/overfitting] A sign of underfitting is that there is a high bias and low variance detected in the current model or algorithm used (the inverse of overfitting: low bias and high variance).
[src:catboost/overfitting] This can be gathered from the Bias-variance tradeoff, which is the method of analyzing a model or algorithm for bias error, variance error, and irreducible error.
[src:catboost/overfitting] With a high bias and low variance, the result of the model is that it will inaccurately represent the data points and thus insufficiently be able to predict future data results (see Generalization error).
[src:catboost/overfitting] As shown in Figure 5, the linear line could not represent all the given data points due to the line not resembling the curvature of the points.
[src:catboost/overfitting] One would expect to see a parabola-shaped line as shown in Figure 6 and Figure 1.
[src:catboost/overfitting] If Figure 5 were to be used for analysis, false predictive results would be given contrary to the results if Figure 6 was analyzed.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Use a different algorithm: If the current algorithm is not able to capture the patterns in the data, it may be necessary to try a different one.
[src:catboost/overfitting] For example, a neural network may be more effective than a linear regression model for some types of data.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Increase the amount of training data: If the model is underfitting due to a lack of data, increasing the amount of training data may help.
[src:catboost/overfitting] This will allow the model to better capture the underlying patterns in the data.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Regularization: Regularization is a technique used to prevent overfitting by adding a penalty term to the loss function that discourages large parameter values.
[src:catboost/overfitting] It can also be used to prevent underfitting by controlling the complexity of the model.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Ensemble Methods: Ensemble methods combine multiple models to create a more accurate prediction.
[src:catboost/overfitting] This can help reduce underfitting by allowing multiple models to work together to capture the underlying patterns in the data.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Feature engineering: Feature engineering involves creating new model features from the existing ones that may be more relevant to the problem at hand.
[src:catboost/overfitting] This can help improve the accuracy of the model and prevent underfitting.
[src:catboost/overfitting] Benign overfitting describes the phenomenon of a statistical model that seems to generalize well to unseen data, even when it has been fit perfectly on noisy training data (i.e., obtains perfect predictive accuracy on the training set).
[src:catboost/overfitting] The phenomenon is of particular interest in deep neural networks, but is studied from a theoretical perspective in the context of much simpler models, such as linear regression.
[src:catboost/overfitting] In particular, it has been shown that overparameterization is essential for benign overfitting in this setting.
[src:catboost/overfitting] In other words, the number of directions in parameter space that are unimportant for prediction must significantly exceed the sample size.
